backends that can be used for api image and video gen with beast2 as the artifact layer frontend






Yes -- Beast2 can treat API generators exactly like local generators:

beast2 frontend
→ generator spec / CDI
→ api backend adapter
→ remote image/video generation
→ artifact saved locally
→ lineage + params + provider metadata stored

best API backends to support

image

1. OpenAI Images API
Good for image generation, editing, inpainting/outpainting-style workflows, and prompt-to-image. Current docs list gpt-image-1.5, gpt-image-1, gpt-image-1-mini, and chatgpt-image-latest for image edits.  ￼

2. Google / Gemini image + Vertex
Useful if you already support Google accounts or want a broader Google media stack. Stronger if paired with Veo for video.

3. Replicate
Best "model zoo API." Useful because Beast2 can expose tons of image/video models through one adapter instead of writing one integration per model.  ￼

4. Stability AI API
Good for SD-style image generation if you want API fallback for users without local GPUs.

5. Fal.ai / Together / Fireworks-style inference APIs
Good for fast hosted open-model inference, especially if Beast2 wants "cloud when local impossible."

video

1. Google Veo / Gemini API / Vertex AI
Probably the most important video API backend. Google docs now describe Veo 3.1 via Gemini API and Veo 3 via Vertex AI video generation API.  ￼

2. Runway API
Strong choice for production video generation APIs; their docs position Runway API for integrating their generative video models into apps/products.  ￼

3. Replicate
Good for open-source video models and experimental models through one common API wrapper.  ￼

4. Luma / Kling / Pika
Worth adapter slots later, but I would not make them core first unless their APIs are stable and terms fit Beast.

Beast2 adapter interface

Use one internal shape:

beastApiGenRequest
  provider
  model
  taskKind: text2image | image2image | text2video | image2video
  prompt
  negativePrompt
  inputArtifactIds
  seed
  width
  height
  durationMs
  fps
  aspectRatio
  providerParamsJson

Result:

beastApiGenResult
  status
  providerJobId
  outputUrls
  downloadedFilePaths
  costEstimate
  providerMetadataJson
  errorText

Then Beast2 stores:

artifact
provider
model
prompt
input artifact ids
remote job id
downloaded media hash
cost
created time
lineage

key design law

API output is not trusted memory until Beast2 downloads it, hashes it, stores it, and records lineage.

remote url is temp
local artifact is truth

This fits your artifact layer perfectly: meta in SQL, big media on filesystem, lineage always recorded.







